#check for missing data
feature_missingValue = {}
Feature_completeValue = {}
for item in prosperLoan.columns:
    if prosperLoan[item].isna().any():
        feature_missingValue[item] = f'{round(prosperLoan[item].isna().sum()/prosperLoan.shape[0] * 100, 2)}%'

Using Heatmap to show relationship between numerical variables¶

Based on the heatmap provided, there is a strong positive correlation between Monthly Loan Payment and Loan Original Amount. This suggests that borrowers who take out larger loans tend to have higher monthly payments.

There is also a weak positive correlation between Loan Original Amount and the number of investors, indicating that loans with higher amounts tend to attract more investors.

Furthermore, there appears to be a slightly weak negative correlation between Borrower APR and Loan Original Amount, as well as between Lender Yield and Loan Original Amount. This suggests that borrowers who take out larger loans may receive lower APRs and that lenders may receive lower yields on larger loans.

There is also a fair negative relationship between Properscore and Lender Yield, indicating that borrowers with lower Properscores may receive higher Lender Yields.

Finally, there is a high positive correlation between Lender Yield and Borrower APR, suggesting that loans with higher Borrower APRs tend to have higher Lender Yields.

Summary of my findings¶

In summary, the features that determine loan amount and loan status include Monthly Loan Payment, Loan Original Amount, Stated Monthly Income, ProsperScore, Borrower APR, Lender Yield, loan term, and employment status.

Loan Amount¶

  • Borrowers with higher incomes, higher ProsperScores, and lower Borrower APRs tend to be approved for larger loan amounts, while unemployed, retiree, and part-time individuals are less likely to be approved for higher loan amounts. Homeowners are also more likely to secure higher loan amounts compared to non-homeowners.

  • The loan term is an important factor in determining the loan amount, with longer-term loans generally associated with higher loan amounts and lower monthly payments compared to short and middle-term loans. Short-term loans are more likely to be paid off, while middle-term loans are more in demand than short-term and long-term loans.

  • Lender Yield is also a factor in determining loan amount, with higher yields generally allowing borrowers to borrow smaller amounts of money. Borrowers with lower ProsperScores may receive higher Lender Yields, while loans with higher Borrower APRs tend to have higher Lender Yields.

  • Employment status also plays a role in determining loan amount, with employed individuals and self-employed individuals having a higher chance of getting approved for higher loan amounts compared to unemployed, retiree, and part-time individuals.

  • Overall, lenders consider various factors when determining loan amounts and status, including income, creditworthiness, loan term, and employment status.

Loan Status¶

  • Loan term: Short-term loans are more likely to be completed compared to long-term loans, which may be more prone to default.

  • Monthly loan payment: Loans with higher monthly payments may be more difficult to pay off and are more likely to become delinquent.

  • Loan amount: Borrowers who take out larger loans may face more difficulty in repaying them, which can increase the likelihood of default.

  • ProsperScore: Loans with low ProsperScore (indicating high risk) are more likely to default compared to loans with high ProsperScore (indicating low risk).

  • Employment status: Retired or part-time workers tend to have the highest lender yield on past due loans, suggesting that they may struggle to make timely payments.

  • Loan purpose: Loans for environmentally friendly projects (i.e., green loans) are more likely to be completed, while loans for other purposes may have a higher default rate
